{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491346"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:43:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:43:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"918"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/918"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.09,0.02,0.54,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"918"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30648"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/918"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"918"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16591"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"573"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"200"},{"type":"contributions","id":"906"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42175"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/30648"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 41-year-old woman presents with two lesions on her nose (Image). They have been present for many years and have not changed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Basal cell carcinoma","Merkel cell tumour","Squamous cell carcinoma","Intradermal naevus","Seborrhoeic keratosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe critical part of dermatology as a student is determining whether a lesion is more likely to be malignant or benign. The lesions pictured are smooth without secondary changes such as ulceration, scale or overtly pigmented. Most importantly, there are two lesions of the same morphology. These features makes it less likely to be malignant in nature. It makes it unlikely to be any malignancy with aggressive nature, such as melanoma or squamous cell carcinoma. It does not rule out basal cell carcinoma which can have a very slow indolent growth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOut of the two options, most students should be aware of the appearance of seborrhoeic keratosis as it is very common and benign. It is often described as a \u0027stuck on wart\u0027 appearance, generally darker and more irregular than the lesion pictured. The photograph describes a typical \u003Cstrong\u003Eintradermal naevus\u003C/strong\u003E which is dome-shaped, non-pigmented and often occurring on the face. Intradermal naevi and nodular basal cell carcinomas (BCC) can have a lot of overlapping features. BCCs can have non-pigmented, dome-shaped, smooth, non-ulcerated but the distinguishing feature is that the nature of the telangiectasia on BCC is arborising, whilst the telangiectasia on intradermal naevi are non-arborising.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Intradermal naevi are benign lesions that do not need any active intervention."],"references":["Ludgate M. Merkel Cell carcinoma. New Zealand: DermNet NZ; 2005 [updated 2014; cited 2020 Dec 22]. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/merkel-cell-carcinoma/","Oakley A. Seborrhoeic keratosis. New Zealand: DermNet NZ; 1997 [updated 2016; cited 2020 Dec 22]. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/seborrhoeic-keratosis/","Emanuel P. Melanocytic naves pathology. New Zealand: DermNet NZ; 2013 [cited 2020 Dec 22]. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/melanocytic-naevi-pathology/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16591"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"918"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18475"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18475"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/37465031-d90b-4753-85cc-fcb05d97690a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/37465031-d90b-4753-85cc-fcb05d97690a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"16591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/16591"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-12-06T17:28:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2022-12-06T17:28:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"918"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"30648"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroup